com.stormpath.sdk.authc
Interface AuthenticationResult

All Superinterfaces:
Resource
All Known Subinterfaces:
AccessTokenResult, ApiAuthenticationResult, OauthAuthenticationResult
public interface AuthenticationResult
extends Resource

An AuthenticationResult represents the return value of an Application authentiation attempt. The successfully authenticated account may be obtained by calling getAccount().

Different Results

A simple account username/password request will result in an AuthenticationResult, but so will authentication attempts by ApiKey (ApiAuthenticationResult), OAuth Bearer Token, (OauthAuthenticationResult, or OAuth via ApiKey as a Client Credentials Grant Type request (AccessTokenResult).

While all of these results allow you to access the calling account via getAccount(), sometimes you may wish to perform specific logic based on the type of result returned. For this, you can use the type-safe AuthenticationResultVisitor interface. For example: 

 AuthenticationResult result = application.authenticateApiRequest(request);

 result.accept(new AuthenticationResultVisitor() {

     @Override
     public void accept(AuthenticationResult result) {
         //do something as a result of a 'normal' successful username/password authentication
     }

     @Override
     public void accept(ApiAuthenticationResult result) {
         //do something as a result of successful ApiKey-based authentication
     }

     ... etc ...

 });

The visitor patten replaces many if-then-else statements with a type-safe interface to guarantee no conditions will be missed at compile time.
